<DocsLayout title="Advanced" description="Advanced tflo topics: checkpointing, async, scripting, and performance.">
  <div class="mx-auto max-w-4xl px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8 py-16">
    <h1 class="text-4xl font-extrabold text-white mb-2">Advanced Topics</h1>
    <p class="text-lg text-text-muted mb-12">Checkpointing, async streams, Kafka, scripting, and performance tuning.</p>

    <!-- Checkpointing -->
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white mt-12 mb-4">Checkpoint &amp; Restore</h2>
    <p class="text-text-muted mb-4">
      tflo can persist window state so your computation can survive restarts without recomputing
      from the beginning of time. Snapshot the graph via
      <a href="https://github.com/matt-cochran/tflo/blob/main/tflo-core/src/compile.rs"><code>CompiledGraph::snapshot()</code></a>,
      persist with a <code>StateStore</code>, and restore later:
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mt-8 mb-3">File-based Checkpoint</h3>
    <CodeBlock code={fileCheckpointCode} src="tflo-examples/examples/docs-file-checkpoint/main.rs" />

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mt-8 mb-3">S3 Checkpoint</h3>
    <CodeBlock code={s3CheckpointCode} src="tflo-examples/examples/docs-s3-checkpoint/main.rs" />

    <p class="text-text-muted mb-4">
      <strong>What is saved:</strong> a snapshot serializes the full per-node state —
      window buffers, running sums, EMA accumulators, detector state machines — with
      <code>postcard</code>, alongside <code>records_seen</code> and <code>min_warmup</code>.
      <code>snapshot()</code> returns a <code>Result</code>: it rejects any graph it cannot
      fully capture (a <code>scan</code>/<code>fold</code> node, or a <code>CustomNode</code>
      without <code>save</code>/<code>load</code>) rather than writing a partial checkpoint.
      After <code>restore()</code>, indicator state resumes exactly where it left off — no
      re-warming, no cold start.
    </p>

    <!-- Async Streams -->
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white mt-12 mb-4">Async Stream Processing</h2>
    <p class="text-text-muted mb-4">
      The <code>async</code> feature on <code>tflo-core</code> provides async adapters that work with any <code>Stream</code>:
    </p>
    <CodeBlock code={asyncStreamCode} src="tflo-examples/examples/docs-advanced/main.rs" />
    <p class="text-text-muted mb-4">
      The async adapter integrates with Tokio. <code>.tflo()</code> yields only computed output values;
      <code>.tflo_with()</code> pairs each input record with its output so you can enrich downstream.
    </p>

    <!-- Kafka -->
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white mt-12 mb-4">Kafka Integration</h2>
    <p class="text-text-muted mb-4">
      <code>tflo-connect-kafka</code> provides a reference implementation pattern for
      integrating tflo with Kafka. The <code>KafkaTfloAdapter</code> wraps keyed execution around
      a Kafka consumer — partitions map to keys, checkpointing coordinates state snapshots
      with offset commits:
    </p>
    <CodeBlock code={kafkaCode} />
    <p class="text-text-muted mb-4">
      <strong>Note:</strong> <code>tflo-connect-kafka</code> is currently a reference design /
      placeholder crate showing the integration pattern. Production Kafka integration
      requires wiring in a Kafka client library (e.g., rdkafka).
    </p>

    <!-- Scripting -->
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white mt-12 mb-4">Multi-Language Scripting</h2>
    <p class="text-text-muted mb-4">
      Define computation rules at runtime without recompiling your Rust binary.
      Each scripting crate provides standalone iterator adapters — they work on regular
      iterators, not through the compiled graph step cycle:
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mt-8 mb-3">CEL (Common Expression Language)</h3>
    <CodeBlock code={celCode} src="tflo-examples/examples/docs-scripting/main.rs" />

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mt-8 mb-3">Rhai</h3>
    <CodeBlock code={rhaiCode} src="tflo-examples/examples/docs-scripting/main.rs" />

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mt-8 mb-3">Rego (OPA Policy)</h3>
    <CodeBlock code={regoCode} src="tflo-examples/examples/docs-scripting/main.rs" />

    <!-- Performance -->
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white mt-12 mb-4">Performance Tuning</h2>

    <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-3 text-text-muted">
      <li>
        <strong class="text-white">Use release profile:</strong>
        <code class="text-primary bg-bg-card px-1 py-0.5 rounded text-sm">cargo build --release</code> with ThinLTO enabled (<a href="https://github.com/matt-cochran/tflo/blob/main/Cargo.toml">see workspace <code>Cargo.toml</code></a>).
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong class="text-white">Prefer count windows over duration windows</strong> when you don&rsquo;t need timestamp-based eviction — they&rsquo;re allocation-free for fixed-size buffers.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong class="text-white">Reuse graphs:</strong> compile once with <code>CompiledGraph::compile(...)</code> and feed data through it repeatedly.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong class="text-white">Batch keyed writes:</strong> when using keyed execution, processing records in key-grouped batches may reduce HashMap lookups.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong class="text-white">Checkpoint periodically, not per-tick:</strong> choose a checkpoint interval that balances recovery time against write overhead.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <div class="mt-16 p-6 rounded-xl border border-border bg-bg-card">
      <p class="text-text-muted">
        <strong class="text-white">Have questions?</strong> Open an issue on <a href="https://github.com/matt-cochran/tflo" class="text-primary hover:underline">GitHub</a> or check the <a href="https://docs.rs/tflo-core" class="text-primary hover:underline">API docs</a>.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
</DocsLayout>
